    <template id="winding_your_automatic_watch_page" name="Winding Your Automatic Watch">
        <t t-call="website.layout">
            <div class="oe_structure">
                <section class="as-offer-services1 pt32 pb32">
                    <div class="container">
                        <div class="seaction-head">
                            <h1>Winding Your Automatic Watch</h1>
                        </div>
                        <div class="seaction-head-desc">
                            <p class="o_default_snippet_text" style="text-align: justify;">
                                An automatic movement, also called a self-winding movement, is a mechanical movement dating to the early 20th century. It winds itself while worn on the wrist, thanks to a weighted rotor in the movement that oscillates
                                with your arm’s motion and provides tension to the mainspring. A slipping clutch prevents the mainspring from getting overwound.&amp;nbsp;
                            </p>
                            <p class="o_default_snippet_text" style="text-align: justify;">
                                <br />
                            </p>
                            <p class="o_default_snippet_text" style="text-align: justify;">An automatic watch eliminates the need for daily hand winding, but if not worn for some time it will stop and will require manual winding to restart.</p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="row">
                            <div class="col-lg-6">
                                <div class="service-box sb-left">
                                    <div class="icon">
                                        <i class="fa fa-shopping-cart" />
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="service-inner">
                                        <h2>If Your Automatic Watch Stops</h2>
                                        <p class="o_default_snippet_text">If your automatic watch stops, restart it manually using the crown&amp;nbsp;</p>
                                        <p>To restart your automatic watch, give the crown about 40 spins, set the time, and then strap it on.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;</p>
                                        <div class="btn-block">
                                            <a href="/watch-service-guide">Return to Watch Service Guide</a>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="col-lg-6">
                                <div class="service-box sb-right">
                                    <div class="icon">
                                        <i class="fa fa-shopping-cart" />
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="service-inner">
                                        <h2>Screw Down Crown</h2>
                                        <p>Always secure the screw-down crown. If your watch has a screw-down crown, be sure to secure it after the watch has been wound and set to ensure the water-tight integrity of the watch.</p>
                                        <div class="btn-block">
                                            <a href="/watch-service-guide">Return to Watch Service Guide</a>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="col-lg-6">
                                <div class="service-box sb-left">
                                    <div class="icon">
                                        <i class="fa fa-shopping-cart" />
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="service-inner">
                                        <h2>Wind Your Watch!</h2>
                                        <p class="o_default_snippet_text">If you don’t wear your automatic watch daily, keep it wound anyway</p>
                                        <p>Manually wind it using the crown at least weekly.</p>
                                        <div class="btn-block">
                                            <a href="/watch-service-guide">Return to Watch Service Guide</a>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="col-lg-6">
                                <div class="service-box sb-right">
                                    <div class="icon">
                                        <span class="fa fa-rotate-right" style="" />
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="service-inner">
                                        <h2>Watch Winders</h2>
                                        <p>
                                            Consider investing in a quality watch winder. A watch winder rotates your watch daily when you’re not wearing it. This ensures that the watch movement continues to run and remains lubricated. Another benefit
                                            is that the time and, especially the date, do not need to be reset, saving wear and tear on the mechanism.
                                        </p>
                                        <p class="o_default_snippet_text">
                                            <br />
                                        </p>
                                        <p>A good watch winder does more than just spin, it allows you to set the rotation based on the requirements of your watch, so beware of cheap ones.</p>
                                        <div class="btn-block">
                                            <a href="/shop/watch-winders">Show Me Watch Winders</a>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>
            </div>
        </t>
